<br>
Thus he has forfeited his right to lead Iraq by violation of these agreements.  We do not need further resolutions, the current resolutions make it quite clear he has no right to maintain his position of power in Iraq unless he proves that he has disarmed.  We are obligated to remove him from power based on current UN resolutions.<br>
<br>
We're just finishing a job as set out by the United Nations.  If they don't want to finish the job they started, it's not our fault.<br>
<br>
The inspections system is only being used as a delay.  It cannot possibly disarm Saddam, and we all know that.  The way it is supposed to work is that the weapons inspectors show up in Iraq and are taken from site to site where they are shown weapons of mass destruction being disassembled.  They are supposed to be able to observe the entire process from start to finish.  An Iraqi declaration of, &quot;Umm, yeah, we got rid of all the weapons.  Umm, that was when we wouldn't let the inspectors in the country.  We don't remember what we did with the pieces&quot; is not going to cut it.  Saddam has turned inspections into a game of hide and go seek.  If you find the weapons, he says, &quot;Woops, my bad, I'll destroy that.&quot;  If you don't find the weapons he gets to keep it.  Of course Bush is not willing to play at this game.  He knows you can't find the weapons hidden underground in a country the size of Texas.  Those countries that are willing to play the inspections game by Saddam's rules do not care about disarming him and are failing to enforce the previous resolutions of the United Nations.  They know it isn't going to work, they just use it as a delay tactic.<br>
<br>
